WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Among the many memories I have of childhood, there are memories of food. Some of it is

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:15.280
[Amit Varma]: the food my mother used to cook. In that generation, alas, you won't find many fathers who did.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:19.760
[Amit Varma]: I loved her short shabatta much, and I also loved her fish ala kheev and the fish pulao

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:25.200
[Amit Varma]: she sometimes packed in my school tiffin box. I can almost taste them as I say these words.

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:29.680
[Amit Varma]: Like any good Bengali boy, I was not a big fan of vegetables, but I did like the aloo

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:34.940
[Amit Varma]: posto she made. I hated pothole and kathal though, and developed a taste for begoon only

00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:40.680
[Amit Varma]: later in life. I remember being a child in Chandigarh in the 1980s, and once in a while,

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.480
[Amit Varma]: my dad would go to empire stores and pick up some packets of salami. My god what a treat

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:50.920
[Amit Varma]: that was. My college years were in Pune, and I remember the special masala dosa of Vaishali

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:55.520
[Amit Varma]: and the banwara of the Ferguson college canteen, and the million cups of cutting chai at the

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:01.640
[Amit Varma]: katta. Food carries such memories with it, and is part of our emotional cells. That's

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:06.560
[Amit Varma]: why we have a phrase like comfort food. There is food that gives us comfort, and it does

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:11.280
[Amit Varma]: so because it takes us to a special place, an earlier place, maybe even when we were

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:16.880
[Amit Varma]: different people, or lived simpler lives, uncomplicated by our modern madness. What's

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:22.600
[Amit Varma]: your comfort food? What food is there in your happy memories? Close your eyes. Can you smell

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:27.680
[Unknown]: it?

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:32.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:40.400
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guests today are Sameer Seth and Yash Banage, who

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:49.760
[Amit Varma]: created waves in Mumbai a few years ago when they started the cult restaurant, Bombay Canteen.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:55.080
[Amit Varma]: They also went on to start my favorite restaurant in Mumbai, O Pedro, as well as Bombay Sweet

00:01:55.080 --> 00:02:01.280
[Amit Varma]: Shop, which takes a modern look at Indian sweets, and it is so so good. Their partner

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:06.520
[Amit Varma]: and mentor, the great chef Floyd Cardoz, passed away in the early days of COVID. But Sameer

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: and Yash kept it together and kept it going. Sameer got in touch with me earlier this year

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:15.760
[Amit Varma]: to discuss a project, Enthoo Cutlet, a bi-monthly food magazine that has just launched. The

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:21.120
[Amit Varma]: link is in the show notes. Meeting him, I realized that all his projects originated

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:26.040
[Amit Varma]: from a place of passion. Sure, he turned his restaurants into successful businesses, but

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:32.240
[Amit Varma]: they began out of a love for food and an appreciation for the role that food plays in our lives.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:37.560
[Amit Varma]: And he was now looking to trace a connection between food and stories, food and identity,

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:41.520
[Amit Varma]: food and memory. That's why Enthoo Cutlet began. I thought Sameer and Yash have had

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:45.720
[Amit Varma]: a fascinating journey. I invited them on the show and here they are. We spoke about how

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:50.120
[Amit Varma]: the culture of dining out has changed in India, how it's different from the West where both

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:55.520
[Amit Varma]: of them have worked, why service should not be confused with servitude, why entrepreneurs

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:59.840
[Amit Varma]: should not obsess about scaling, what the food industry has in common with the creator

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:04.920
[Amit Varma]: economy, and just their personal journeys, which I found so fascinating and instructive.

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:09.760
[Amit Varma]: When Sameer left his corporate job to get into this business, his grandmother told him,

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:15.240
[Amit Varma]: bang chhor ke parathe beshne ja rahe ho. My response to that is, no banker has ever been

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:19.840
[Amit Varma]: on the scene and the unseen. Before we begin this conversation though, let's take a quick

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:20.840
[Amit Varma]: commercial break.

